1. Network Policy:
There are three pods where the applications deployed. Front-end, API Server, Database Server.

User(request) ---> Front-end ---> API-Server --> Database
Database(response)---> API-Server --> Front-end ---> User

Ingress: Incoming traffic
Step 1: User --> Front-end (ingress traffic from user)
Step 3: Front-end ---> API-Server (ingress traffic from frontend)
Step 5: API-Server --> Database (ingress traffic from apiserver)


Egress: Outgoing traffic
Step 2: Front-end ---> API-Server (egress traffic for frontend)
Step 4: API-Server --> Database (egress traffic for apiserver)


Here all the pods doesn't required to connect each due to network policy implemented.
POD A reach POD B
POD B reach POD C
POD A not reach POD C (network policy applied in the POD C where the ingress traffic should be only from POD B)

Ingress traffic:::
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: test-network-policy
  namespace: default
spec:
  podSelector:
    matchLabels:
      role: db
  policyTypes:
  - Ingress
  ingress:
  - from:
    - podSelector:
        matchLabels:
          role: frontend
    ports:
    - protocol: TCP
      port: 6379




Important network policy:

apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: test-network-policy
  namespace: default
spec:
  podSelector:
    matchLabels:
      role: db
  policyTypes:
  - Ingress
  - Egress
  ingress:
  - from:
    - ipBlock:
        cidr: 172.17.0.0/16
        except:
        - 172.17.1.0/24
    - namespaceSelector:
        matchLabels:
          project: myproject
    - podSelector:
        matchLabels:
          role: frontend
    ports:
    - protocol: TCP
      port: 6379
  egress:
  - to:
    - ipBlock:
        cidr: 10.0.0.0/24
    ports:
    - protocol: TCP
      port: 5978

Step 1: 
  podSelector:
    matchLabels:
      role: db
the match lables for the network policy is role:db


Step 2:
policyTypes:
  - Ingress
  - Egress

Policy type is ingress and egress

Step 3:
ingress:
  - from:
    - ipBlock:
        cidr: 172.17.0.0/16
        except:
        - 172.17.1.0/24
    - namespaceSelector:
        matchLabels:
          project: myproject
    - podSelector:
        matchLabels:
          role: frontend
    ports:
    - protocol: TCP
      port: 6379

POD B (api pod) frontend label --> POD C (database pod)

Database pod's port is 6379 and tcp protocol.

Database pod should decide the ingress traffic, based on podSelector (frontend role). Only the api pod will reach to database.

Namespace label is myproject for production, so only the api pod from the production environment will reach the database pod.

There is an database backup server which has to query from database, only the server IP 172.17.0.0/16 will reach database except -
 172.17.1.0/24


Step 4: 

egress:
  - to:
    - ipBlock:
        cidr: 10.0.0.0/24
    ports:
    - protocol: TCP
      port: 5978

Database pod will allow the outgoing traffic to the database backup server ip 10.0.0.0/24 with port 5978



Note:
If a pod allow ingress traffic from the other pods, outgoing traffic to the same pods will happen automatically. Specific policy configuration
is not required.



2. Custom Resource Defintion

Resource like deployment.yml we create and the details like create, list, modify will be updated in ETCD. 
Controller will monitor the ETCD always and do the changes in the cluster like watch the replicas count and make the desire state.

Resource ---> ETCD <----Controller


But when we want to customize the resource creation, we need to create a custom resource defintion file first and declare the details we
need.
Eg: 
If we want to book a flight tickets with the fligh.yml defintion file
then we need to understand the requirement like what is the apiversion, kind, metadata and spec. Declare all info in the CRD.yaml file


Now create the CRD.yaml file
then create flights.yml file

Note: We need a custom controller to monitor the resource created using CRD.yml defintion file

3. Custom Controllers
Based on custom resource defintion, fligh ticket object is created and the info stored in ETCD.
Custom controllers will Monitor ETCD and change the request based on the object in ETCD.
Custom controller will use Flight ticekt API to book, cancel, modify it based on the object in ETCD.

Note: Custom Controller will be created using go/python language. It will define how API can be used from custom controller.
GO Install
git clone custome/controller file

Docker image has to be created with the above files.
POD/Deployment will be created using docker image

4. Operator Framework
A new resource is created using custom resource definition. Custom controller will monitor/change the CRD object in ETCD.

The above all steps will created in a single framework using Operator.

Flight.yaml will create a new resource, Custom resource definition, custom controller.

Exampple: ETCD Operator will do kind of below in a single framework
ETCD Cluster ETCD Controller
ETCD Backup  Backup Operator
ETCD Restore 




